# Ship Bar: Complete Inline (Default Git Workflow)

**Single source of truth. All steps are inline here — do not substitute a cross-reference for actually reading the step.**

Every repo change follows: `agent/<slug>` branch → PR to `main` → CI → wait gate → thread closure → merge → deploy → verify:prod.

---

## 9-step ship bar

All steps are required unless the user **explicitly waives that step in writing for that PR**.

### Step 1 — Branch
```
git fetch origin
git checkout main && git pull origin main
git checkout -b agent/<topic-slug>        # or feat/ or fix/
```
Use a distinctive slug (topic + short nonce like `-kj1` for generic topics). Never reuse another agent's in-flight branch. Check for collisions before pushing.

### Step 2 — Commit and push
Commit only on the topic branch. `git push -u origin HEAD`.

### Step 3 — PR
`gh pr create --base main`. One PR per deliverable. Fix-ups stay on the same branch; do NOT open a second PR.

### Step 4 — CI green
`gh pr checks <n> --watch` until `ci_result` passes. Fix forward on **this** PR. After fix pushes, `@mention` reviewers using handles from `gh pr view -c` (not display names).

### Step 5 — Wait gate (hard; DO NOT skip)
**Do NOT merge in the same breath as CI green. Stop. Then:**

a. Run `npm run wait-for-bots` — exits 2 with time remaining if < 20 min since `ci_result` green. **Do not proceed until it exits 0.**
b. `gh pr view <n> --comments`
c. `gh api repos/<owner>/<repo>/pulls/<n>/reviews`
d. `gh api repos/<owner>/<repo>/pulls/<n>/comments`
e. On github.com: scan Conversation + Files tabs until in-flight bot activity (reactions, pending review) settles.
f. Note ALL bots that commented after your last push: Gemini Code Assist, Codex, Copilot, CodeRabbit, Greptile, Sourcery, security scanners, etc.

**The 20-minute minimum wait is unconditional — it applies even when early bot threads already exist. Bots post in waves; early threads do not mean all bots have finished. Calling "no more feedback" before 20 min is a policy violation.**

### Step 6 — Thread closure (hard; DO NOT skip)
For **every** substantive thread (bot or human):
- Enumerate all distinct threads.
- Judge each: implement / defer / decline.
- Reply **in-thread on GitHub** (preferred): "implemented in `<sha>`" / "deferred — `<reason>`" / "declined — `<reason>`".
- If GitHub inline replies unavailable: append `## Feedback responses` to PR body with each item.

Do NOT merge with unanswered substantive threads.

### Step 7 — Merge
Only after steps 5–6: `gh pr merge --squash`.
**Do NOT enable auto-merge before steps 5–6** — `pr-auto-merge.yml` merges on CI alone and will merge before you reply to bots.

### Step 8 — Deploy confirmed
Wait for Cloudflare Pages and/or Workers to finish deploying. Push ≠ deployed. Confirm in Cloudflare dashboard or `gh run watch`.

### Step 9 — Production verify
```
npm run verify:prod -- --scope=auto --depth=smoke
```
From repo root. Report the exit code. Use `--scope=full --depth=full` for shared/tooling/workflow/verification changes or explicit full sign-off. If exit non-zero: fix, redeploy, re-run — loop until 0.

---

## Closeout checks (run before claiming task complete on a topic branch)

```
npm run ship:closeout:strict && npm run wait-for-bots
```

- `ship:closeout:strict` exit 2 = open PR still exists → continue steps 5–9.
- `wait-for-bots` exit 2 = < 20 min since `ci_result` green → wait and re-sweep bots.

---

## Forbidden completions (never say these while an open PR exists and you have merge ability)

- "Done" / "shipped" / "production updated"
- "PR opened, here's the link" (when you could continue)
- "CI green so we're good"
- "Handing off the PR" (when you could merge)
- "Merge-ready" without having completed steps 5–6

---

## Hard constraints (urgency/tone never waive steps 5–7)

User phrases that do NOT waive the wait gate or thread closure: "merge everything", "batch merge", "just merge", "urgency", "ASAP", frustration/frustration tone, "CI passed". None of these substitute for an **explicit written waiver of bot closeout for that PR**.

Exception: user provides an explicit written waiver for that specific PR → may skip bot closure for that PR only.

---

## After merge

`npm run git:graph-hygiene` (or `git fetch origin --prune`); delete local topic branch.

---

## Exceptions

- User orders `main` hotfix: push directly to `main`; still do steps 8–9 after deploy.
- Already on a named feature branch: continue there; rebase/merge `origin/main` if stale.
- Written waiver of bot closeout for that PR: may merge/skip gate for that PR only.

---

## Bot/reviewer reply standard (steps 5–6 detail)

Treat automated reviewers like humans for **substantive** feedback (behaviour, correctness, security, architecture, enforced-policy hygiene — not trivial spelling unless meaning changes). Covered bots: `gemini-code-assist`, `chatgpt-codex-connector`, `copilot`, `coderabbit`, `sourcery-ai`, `greptile`, security scanners.

- **Accepted:** commit fix on same branch + in-thread reply with SHA.
- **Deferred:** in-thread reply with reason + optional `docs/REFACTOR_BACKLOG.md` link.
- **Declined:** in-thread reply with concrete reason (out of scope, conflicts with `AGENTS.md`, etc.).

Do NOT claim "no actionable feedback" from a single top-level review comment without also checking all inline file-level threads for that bot — top-level text is often generic while file comments carry P1/P2 items.
